segments.text: and the walls were hard stucco.
In each room we had a laboratory where we could brush our teeth and shave.
One laboratory.
There were two closets, one on either side of the room in those buildings, so that each room, each person in the room had a private closet.
And

As I say, the front doors were steel and the contractor had misjudged, either the contractor misjudged the size of the door opening or they thought that this was going to be a good ventilating program to make those doors too sharp.
And so each door was this far from the floor
And so, as a result, if anybody down the hall hollered, it just reverberated through that door.
Was there space over the door?
No.
Okay.
So, no.
It fit tight above the door and no transom.
Now in the other depot dorms, every door had a transom up above.
You could crawl up through the transom and crawl into the room.
But in these dorms, they didn't.
They had the steel door.
But they...
They were about this much too sharp.

Later on, I understand, they came in, I'm sure they did what I said, and they built an attachment and they took those doors off and screwed on the extensions of the doors so that they eliminated the sound problem.
Did anything ever happen under that door?
Oh yeah, oh yeah.
Many things happened under those doors.
They'd throw live fire over there and everything else.
Some of those old dorms, they'd build a fire right outside the door, and they'd knock on the door, and they'd all run and go open that door and have a bunch of deuce breaking and burning.
I think.
Was it possible to crawl under that door?
No.
Wasn't that how it was?
It wasn't quite that high.
You couldn't crawl under it.
But you could sure throw things under it.
All right.
The new dorms then, the rooms seem bigger, nicer.
rooms were nicer, cleaner, more modern, more up-to-date, had a nice big window.
And they had a, what do you call these things that give off heat?
Radiators.
Radiators.
They had radiators.
They heated the rooms with steam heat from the tunnels.
And so you all filled those dorms up.
Filled them up.
But the core could not all be accommodated over there.
Most of the core was accommodated over there, but not the whole core.
And so they still had core in the Walton Hall.
They had core in Law and Puryear Hall.
They had core in Goodwin Hall.
Somewhere along was stopped being used as a dormitory, but not at that time.
Goodwin Hall and Mitchell Hall, Law and Puryear, Hart Hall,
were all still used by the Corps.
Alright, so you're a sophomore.
How much better was it to be a sophomore than a fish?
Well, it was much better.
It was much better as sophomores so we had responsibilities.
We were ordered to try to treat the incoming freshmen as we were treated.
And I guess we did.
We tried to
teach those incoming freshmen how to know everybody in the in the outfits by name and where they were from.
I guess we mistreated them to some extent but not too badly.
We had a lot of students dropping out in those days.
About, do you remember anything about the
survival rate of your freshman class next year?
About how many?
I'm gonna guess, and see company, I'm gonna guess that out of say, say we had 30 freshmen, by the time we came back there were 20, so what would that be?
We would drop from, say, 30 to 20.
That's a third, isn't it?
We lost a lot to academics.
We lost a lot to kids who just weren't happy.
And we lost some to the economy.
So the pressure is still going on.
As far as you can recall, about how much money did you bring with you as a freshman?
Well, I brought about $25.
And I brought a check that my dad had given me.
And I wrote a check on him for my fees.
Do you remember what that was?
I can tell you what I went to school on for two semesters.
I went to school as A&M and paid all my room and board and everything for about $360.
And you didn't have a job?
Not at that time, not as a freshman.
I got a job as a sophomore for Mr. Walter, P.M. Walter.
And what happened was that Chick Sale, who was a lieutenant and also had something to do with advertising for the battalion,
And I got involved with Chick some way, or he had issued a call for volunteers to sell advertising for the battalion.
And I went down there and volunteered to sell advertising.
And they put me in downtown Bryan, calling on Walters and WSD and Jack Lester and some of those men.
Called on Alistair Wallerup and sold him advertising for the tag.
And then the next summer, I had a letter from Mr. Wallerup wanting to know if I wanted to go to work for him.
And I said, oh, yes.
He said, I'd like for you to come a week early so you can be here to help sell these beautiful arms.
So then I worked for Mr. Wallerup all my sophomore and junior year.
About how many hours a week?
Well, I would work all afternoon Saturday.
That would be about five hours.
But we stayed open until 5 or 6 hours on Saturday.
I'd work about 12 hours a week and he'd pay me 50 cents an hour.
So I was making $12, I was making $6 an hour.
And you were a salesman?
I was a salesman.
How did you get back and forth from downtown?
I rode the bus.
And do you remember what it cost?
Ten cents.
Ten cents.
Ran about how often?
It ran about every hour.
Every hour.
I'd catch the bus right there to the corner where Mr. Walters' store was on the corner.
I'd catch it there, say, I'd catch that bus at 5.30 so I could make formation for, because I was the first sergeant.
in the K Company, and I had to leave the company in for mess.
And then my senior year, well I didn't work my senior year, but my sophomore year I was, I wasn't private, I wasn't, I guess I was a corporal or whatever they were, sophomore year.
Then I became a first sergeant.
While I was in my junior year, I had to leave the,
call them to order and get them all in and so forth.
So I had to leave in that town.
But I was making about, what?
I was making more than $6 a week.
I was making about $10, $12.
Right.
And so you mentioned selling uniforms?
Yes.
Waldrop sold?
Yeah.
What were these, optional uniforms?
Optional uniforms, like shirts, and ornaments, and ties, socks, slacks, khaki slacks.
And also, remember, Aden Academy was a pretty big factory in those days.
And those boys had to buy all their uniforms.
And Mr. Waldrop was the main supplier of uniforms.
Was he the largest men's clothing store?
Yes.
His was the largest men's.
Another store across the street was WSD, but Mr. Morton did more business than anybody else.
Alright, let's digress on downtown.
Alright.
Who were the major businesses downtown?
Well, Caldwell Jewelry, a place called Creamland that was right by the Old Palace Theater.
Palace Theater, across the street was the Dixie Theater.
On the corner there was Mr. McQueen's Drugstore.
Then the next building was Mr. Walter's, me and Walter.
Then next door was the Collegiate Shop, which was a ladies shoe and dress shop.
And then another spot down was Mr. Jack Lester's
a ladies shop, and Mr. John Seely Caldwell had a jewelry store, and Sankey Park had a jewelry store.
Was there a five and ten cent store?
Yes, there was a F.W.
Woolworth across the street, and there was a Perry's.
And there were several eating restaurants.
There was the LaSalle Hotel active, and they had a coffee shop in the LaSalle Hotel.
There was a Charles Hotel across the street from the LaSalle Hotel with a small coffee shop in it.
American Steam Laundry, Central Texas Hardware was where it was.
The banks, the First State Bank.
the City National Bank, the First National Bank, all there downtown.
There was Howell Lumber Company, Parker Lumber Company.
There was an automobile dealership, two of them downtown.
One was a postmobile, one was a Nash & Rambler, and another was the Plymouth and
Well, the railroad station was on the east end of, I mean the west end of the downtown area.
The railroad station was on the west end of the downtown station.
Now, but by this creamery was the barbershop.
By the barbershop was the Carnegie Library.
And on the other side of the Carnegie Library was
Charles Hotel and a few little places along there.
Way down at the east end of Main Street, was there an ice house?
Yes.
Right at the end was an ice house.
The street was real wide, you know, they say it was designed so that a buggy with a team of mules or horses could make a U-turn downtown.
But at the end was the old ice house.

old shoemaker i think shoemaker wholesale grocery and ice house how often would an aggie student go downtown to the movie about every saturday night oh really yeah maybe maybe not on average quite that much but it was a usual thing to go to downtown ryan to go to movies on saturday night that was a big
a problem with us students because we thought that she ought to have a movie house on the station.
And she always promised us one, but never would provide one.
So there wasn't a movie theater?
No.
Oh, I didn't know the campus wasn't there yet.
No, there was not a movie theater, except the free one, which was in the old... Go ahead.
No, it was in the old...
Assembly Hall, they called it.
And I'll tell you where it was located.
It was right there where the chapel is.
And they tore that down to build it.
How often were those free movies?
Every Sunday after lunch, they were free.
We'd have lunch in the dining hall in Hedford.
And they sold popcorn for about a nickel a big sack.
That whole floor would be full of popcorn.
But we had no movie house in College Station until finally the campus theater was built.
And it was built about my senior year.
Matter of fact, I was in that movie when we got word that Japan had returned to Pearl Harbor.
Describe that.
We had lunch in the dining hall.
Robert Taylor in a yank at Oxford.
We went to the movie.
By then, it would just be blank.
When everybody got in, we'd go to the start and have all the preliminary stuff.
But anyway, we went through that.
And then the movie started.
I guess it had to be nine or ten minutes.
And somebody talking on the phone, checking in with my guest, said that they just learned that the Japanese have attacked Pearl Harbor.
And that the show would be shut down.
And that every person in the movie theater should go to his door and wait on it.
I turned to Bob Russell, my friend and classmate who I was with, and I said, Bob, where's Pearl Harbor?
We didn't know where Pearl Harbor was.
But we went to the room and turned the radio on, and we all listened.
Of course, they were all hunting with the attack on Pearl Harbor and trying to give us news about it.
What did, that night and so forth, what did you all think that would mean to you?
We didn't know what it would mean to us.
We thought that they might just take us right out and put us in the service.
We didn't know, but we stayed on our radios until we got to classes the next day and they called meetings all over the campus and within a week,
after they attacked Pearl Harbor, they totally changed our program.
First thing they did, we didn't like it in our class, nearly threw in their rank, they said all seniors, all students will go to breakfast every morning.
We didn't like it.
All students will take calisthenics every morning before they go to practice.
So they put a lot of new rules in immediately, all for our benefit.
And as far as you know, those decisions were made on the campus.
There wasn't an order from Washington.
There was no order from Washington.
I've gathered that the rules were made that were changed, were made by the administration on the campus, looking to the fact
that we were gonna, we were in a war and we were gonna have to do things all different.
And I was put under tremendous pressure as president of the senior class because I had all the boys that were seniors, they were saying, well we'll just give up our contracts.
And I had to deal with that.
And I finally took some of the leaders of the class, plus some of the biggest rabble-rousers, and I went to Houston.
I called Colonel I. Gashburn, who was my good friend,
I said, I've got to bring these boys down, and this whole city class is about to walk out.
And I said, I don't want them to walk out.
I want them to stay here.
And I took some of them.
I figured the worst rabble-rousers, I'd just take them.
And I took some of them with me.
And he talked to us up in his office for about two hours.
He said, boys, it's a war.
By that time, he was head of the, he'd just been made governor.
A little later, he was head of the Chamber of Commerce at the time.
But he was later made head of the top shipyard.
But anyway, he told a decent boy, he said, this thing is important.
And we came back, and he kind of persuaded them.
We called a meeting, and these rabble-rabblers got up and said, hell, I was against this whole thing, but now I'm part of it.
You've got to keep your connections.
Now, they were not thinking about resigning their commission to avoid active duty, were they?
No, no.
It was a protest over having to...
These routines.
Yeah, protest against the routines.
Not to avoid active duty.
They were perfectly willing to fight.
Right.
But they just didn't like the idea of the administration telling them they had to change their routine.
You know how Aggies are.
Do you remember in those first few nights, do you remember talking with friends, maybe after the light was turned off in your room and so forth, about what it might mean in your lives?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
We discussed it.
What kind of a...
combat we were going to be in.
As a matter of fact, several of my friends and I transferred from the infantry into the Air Force, not necessarily to get away from the infantry.
But more important, we felt like the Air Force was going to be a more glamorous thing to be in and more exciting.
And I did transfer and stayed four years in the Air Force, but I never got to fly because
By the time I got ready to fly and applied for my flight school, I was already a captain in the Air Force.
And I got promoted in 90 days from a second lieutenant to a first lieutenant.
And then I got promoted in six months, which was the minimum you could serve a first lieutenant to be a captain.

six months I was promoted to captain and I applied for the flying school and I got turned down because not necessarily turned down but they said we are not taking captains in grade in flying school they said now if you want to revert to a second lieutenant we will enroll you in flying school and I said I don't want to drop two levels back to go to flying school
So I turned it back.
You go on active duty after graduation?
The day after graduation.
In 42?
In 42.
During that, those six months or so from Pearl Harbor to graduation, did the conduct, the behavior of the Corps members change?
Did things become more serious?
Things became very much more serious.
They gave us a Christmas holiday.
But it was one week where we hadn't been getting two weeks.
We got five days off for Christmas.
We all came back.
They eliminated what was spring break, and they eliminated any other holidays.
And so they graduated us two weeks early, escalated our
And so, we graduated on May the 15th.
And I reported to active, we were commissioned on the afternoon of May 15th.
And I reported to active duty at Ellington Field in Houston on May 16th.
I never even went home.
My mother and daddy came down here from Greenville to see me graduate, and then they left and went back to Greenville, and I went to Ellicott.
Are you the oldest?
No, I was the middle.
Okay, so you were not the first?
No, I was the middle.
I was the third one to go to college.
What were their feelings, as far as you could tell,
at graduation, knowing you were going to have to go on active duty right then?
Well, they were concerned.
Because I was the first one in my family to go in the military.
My older brother came in after I went in, and my brother-in-law came in after I, so I was the first one in my family.
My father was very proud of the fact that I was going.
He seemed not concerned about
My mother was concerned, though I don't think either one of them really realized what was ahead for all of us.
I don't think they had much comprehension about what was going to happen.
But we didn't know either.
We knew we were in a war and we know there's going to be a lot of shooting and a lot of death and a lot of terrible things happen.
We were ready for it.
I mean, we didn't, we weren't dodging any traps or shirking any dead people.
Did you know anybody back home in Greenwood or anywhere else that you thought of that did try to avoid?
I didn't know a single soul.
I knew a lot of people, being a leader of the class, I didn't know a single Aggie that attempted to avoid 100% service.
Now I did have some friends who were not able to go in because they couldn't pass.
They physically couldn't.
And they were very upset about the fact that they wouldn't take them in because they had diabetes
a heart flutter or some physical problem that would just not let them go in.
And so they had to do something else, but I don't know of any, anybody that tried to avoid service.
Were any of the, this is a turning point, were any of the Kishy boys here then?
No, I don't think so, but there was,
There was Yee, Henry Yee.
What about Henry Kawahata?
Kawahata was here.
As a matter of fact, Henry Kawahata was over there, close to C Company.
I guess Henry was in A Company.
Henry Kawahata, Henry Yee, Howard Chang,
another Japanese boy, I don't know his name, that the FBI thought may be a sympathizer.
Did any students pick on them, tease them?
No.
Actually, Chang was a Hawaiian, and Chang
left A&M shortly after and went back to Hawaii because they attacked him.
So he didn't finish his semester.
When I was in Kunming, China, I got out of the plane and went in to the operations officer in Kunming, China.
Here was Henry Yee.
He was a class of 41, a year ahead of me.
And he was a captain.
I spoke to him.
We had a good visit.
He was as busy as any American you could find.
I'm not sure whether he was Chinese or Japanese.
I think he was Chinese.
But anyway, it was a wonderful experience to see the willingness of the young men of Texas at that time who wanted to
be of service at that time.
At that commencement, do you remember what it was like, who the speaker was, what the emphasis was?
Yes, I can tell you.
I can tell you.
We had the graduation commencement exercise at the U end of Kyle Field.
Tom Gillis was
cadet colonel and valedictorian of the class.
He was cadet colonel and valedictorian.
He got the months.
He couldn't function as the valedictory address.
So they called on our friend Fred Smith to give it in Tom's place.
So Tom presented the valedictory address that, I mean Fred did, in Tom's name.
Anyway, they had a man coming
from Dallas to make the commencement address.
For some reason, he was delayed getting there.
So old General Breeze, his picture's in that manual I saw, General Breeze, they called on him to give an extemporaneous speech.
He stood up and made a 45 minute extemporaneous speech.
Right at the end of his speech, the real
And so then they introduced him, and he made his 45-minute speech.
So we got two, a double barrel full of commencement speeches.
And then that afternoon, about 1.30 or 2 o'clock, we went to Guy Hall.
And we were commissioned.
We got commissioned.
I know.
Uh, was, did the commissioning speaker have anything memorable to say about what y'all were headed into?
I don't remember hardly a thing about what they had to say.

The most meaningful one that I remember talking about it was Colonel Eichmann when I had those boys down in his office about what, you see he'd been a major in World War I and he'd been in the trenches.
And he knew what was coming up.
And he just talked, put serious talk right to it and said, boys, I don't know whether you realize it or not, but we're in a terrible war.
And he said, you're going to have to fight.
You're going to have to go.
You're going to be in a shooting war.
And we really, outside of this conversation, I don't remember what these two people, I was so excited about that.
And I think most of them.
As a matter of fact, I've talked to my classmates frequently, and I said, what did they say?
We had two commencement addresses.
Do you remember a damn thing any one of them said?
None of them.
Was commencement then, about like it is now, every name called, every hand shaken?
Right.
All right, so your mom and dad came down.
Right.
Did you give them some of your belongings?
Yes, I did.
They took them back to Greenville.
That's my diploma.
That's my diploma.
I gave them everything that I didn't need, and they took it back to Greenwood.
And did you have a car by then?
My brother had given me a car.
He had a little, he'd been drafted into the service.
He had a little 39 Ford Coupe, which he gave to me.
So you drove that to Ellicott?
I drove that to Ellicott Field, and then we were there two weeks, and we got orders to go to MacDill Field, Florida, and Warren Ringo, and
Bill Bannister and I got in that little Ford and drove to the park.
Alright, let's go back and recall some students.
Memorable teachers, advisors, people that made a difference for you.
